# ## Background
# 
# We often use computers to complete complex mathematical tasks. One task of interest is computing the derivative of a function, that is finding **f’(x)** for a given function **f(x)**. It turns out that this task can be very cumbersome. However, we can use a technique called numerical differentiation to estimate the value of the derivate of a function at a given point. That is, instead of finding the general function **f’(x)**, we can approximate **f’(a)** where **a** is some real number.
# 
# One of the simplest methods of numerical differentiation is using a technique called differencing approximations. One of the most popular differencing approximation techniques is forward differencing. Let’s say you want to compute the derivative of your function f at the point x. The idea of this method is to compute the slope of a line from **f(x)** to **f(x+h)**, where h is a very small number (representing a small change in x). Figure 1 demonstrates what this method looks like:
# 
# ![Figure 1](data:image/png;base64,)
# 
# Thus, we can approximate **f’(x)** using **forward differencing** with the following formula:
# 
# <br/><br/>
# \begin{align}
#   f'(x) \approx \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \tag{1}
# \end{align}
# <br/><br/>
# 
# There are two additional difference approximation techniques. These are backwards differencing and centered differencing. A depiction of all 3 methods are show in Figure 2. 
# 
# 
# ![Figure 2]![Figure 2](data:image/png;base64,)
# 
# The formulas for approximating the derivative at point x for each method are given in the table below.
# 
# | Method | Formula   |
# |------|------|
# |   **Forward Differencing**  | \begin{align}
#   f'(x) \approx \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \tag{1}
# \end{align}|
# |   **Backwards Differencing**  | \begin{align}
#   f'(x) \approx \frac{f(x)-f(x-h)}{h} \tag{2}
# \end{align}|
# |   **Central Differencing**  | \begin{align}
#   f'(x) \approx \frac{f(x+h)-f(x-h)}{2h} \tag{3}
# \end{align}|
# 
# It is your team’s job to develop a program for evaluating the derivative of a function at a given point using all three methods.
# 

